MACINTOSH SE

•	What year was it made? 1987
•	What operating system does it run? The original operating system is Mac OS: System 4.1, but the computer will run MacOS: Systems 2.0-7.01. 
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List). In 1987, the Macintosh SE cost $3,700, but today that would be adjusted to about $7,749.97. I found 37 different Macintosh SEs listed on eBay, ranging from $25.49 all the way to $1,300 for one that comes with its original keyboard, mouse, and a lot of software. There were none listed on Craigslist however. 
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
Some strengths of Macintosh SE included a longer life span because of the incorporation of a cooling fan in the computer. Other strengths included its compact shape and packaging as well as its internal floppy disk drive. This model also made use of a keyboard and mouse interface (which seeing the Kaypro, is all the more notable now). However, the SE didn’t come bundled with a keyboard. Also, it was a little chunkier than other compact computers that had preceded it—weighing a half-pound more. This model is best known for its long life span and incorporation of multiple inputs for extensions as well as its internal floppy disk drives. 

Turn it on (you must figure out how). Read some of Deena Larsen’s Marble Springs. Quit Marble Springs. What else is on this Mac?
There is a plethora of other applications on this Mac, including notepad, a puzzle, an alarm clock, a calculation, a control panel, key caps, and scrapbook. There is also a copy of We Descend by Bill Bly and Miss Sing. 
Extra Notes: The little markers on the keyboard for your hands are on the D and K, which is so different from my current keyboard that it actually made it hard for me to type because I kept misplacing my hands. 
There actually weren’t many noticeable differences for me expect maybe how many inputs there were—my mac air is very minimal and seeing the compact computer’s internal floppy drives made me reminisce for internal disk drives and the days when I could watch DVDs on my computer. 
