VECTREX

•	What year was it made? 1982
•	What operating system does it run? MOS 6522 Versatile Interface Adapter
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List). In 1982, the Vectrex retailed at $199; today it would cost $490.68 if it were adjusted for inflation. eBay had 8 different Vectrexes for sale ranging in price from $49 to $599 for a Vectrex with its original box and extra games. There were no Vectrexes for sale on Craigslist.
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
One highlight of the Vectrex is its durability—it doesn’t have to be compatible with computers or televisions, so compared to many gaming counsels it doesn’t become outdated as quickly. Other highlights included the ease of use and design of the controller, as well as the well-designed games that mimicked the graphics of popular arcade games. 

Turn it on (you must figure out how). Play MineStorm. Try another cartridge. Why do you think the designer’s would have opted for the “vector” graphics?
The Vectrex went on to incorporate 3D imaging and more advanced graphics, which would have been made easier by using “vector” graphics, which as outlines of 2D images were easier to reproduce three dimensionally than pixelated raster graphics. Also, I think that the Vectrex was imitating popular arcade games that used vector graphics—the console has the feel of an at home arcade rather than just a computer game (from the controller to the counsel itself which was stand-alone), the graphics seem to compliment this. 
===================================================================================================================
AMIGA

•	What year was it made? !985
•	What operating system does it run? Amiga OS
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List). When it was released the Amiga cost $1,295, but today, adjusted for inflation, it would cost $2,863.74.  Two Amigas were listed for sale on eBay (both between $100 and $300), but neither included a monitor. There were no Amigas for sale on Craigslist. 
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
The Amiga is best known for its ability to handle sophisticated graphics, including animated graphics, and games. A chipset that processes audio and visual data separately from the CPU allows the Amiga to run smoother graphics, audio, and animation than other models we’ve seen. The Amga was also reasonably priced and known as one of the first personal, multitasking computers. However, the downside to the ability to multitask is that the Amiga did not have the memory to restore files if there was a sudden shutdown. Also, the Amiga was prone to crashing, which seems like a big weakness for consumers. 

Turn it on (you must figure out how). Try the demos. What else can it do? (Hint: try the “Amiga Appetizer” disk). Have a look at the Amiga magazines and the book, The Future Was Here.
Notes: The Appetizer disk is funny—I was really amused by the paint functions like “Dots” that just seemed to show off the Amiga’s ability to create smooth animated graphics. The Amiga can do many things though: it has a notepad, a calculator, clock, work bench, and the appetizer disk allows the user to “paint,” “write,” create music, and a play a tile game. While The Future is Here really emphasizes the Amiga’s graphics, I was not so impressed I suppose not knowing enough to be impressed really. Instead, I noticed most how this computer seemed to function like my computer, except with the addition of needing to use floppy disks to access most things. Though it was nice that there was some basic functionality beyond what was made accessible through the floppies. 


