MACINTOSH IIci

•	What year was it made? 1989
•	What operating system does it run? MAC OS 6.04-7.1.1
•	How much did it cost (then and now, adjusted for inflation)? How hard is it to find one on the secondhand market (check eBay and Craig’s List). Originally, the Macintosh IIci cost $6,269, today that would be about $12,029.65. There were four separate Macintosh IIci computers (including monitors) for sale on eBay, and their prices varied from $49 to $549 for working models with software. I once again had no luck with Craigslist.
•	In brief (a short paragraph), what were its historical strengths and weaknesses as a platform? What was it best known for?
Historical strengths of this Mac include its computing power, which was apparently 56% more powerful than its predecesers as it was the first to reach the 16MHz mark according to Dan Knight’s “Was the Macintosh IIci the Best Mac Ever?.” Additionally, the IIci was known for being an durable personal computer with excellent graphics, and many enthusiasts seem to enjoy the ability to add extensions and cache cards to the Mac to make certain upgrades. One downside of this Mac, however is that it did not have a built in display, and it’s expandability (ability to add on extensions) seems to have meant that different users had vastly different experiences. 

Turn it on (you must figure out how). Open WordPerfect. Open MS Word. Try typing a simple document in each. Which do you like better, and why? Open MacPaint. Try drawing something. (You don’t need to save any of your work from these applications.) What else is on this Mac? What can you learn about its past user(s)?
I absolutely prefer Microsoft Word to WordPerfect—I love that Word makes it so much easier to insert tables/pictures/drawings into your documents than WordPerfect. I even miss that MS Paint use to pop open and integrate with Word to make drawing simple shapes pretty easy. I also like that the icons are more intuitive and extensive in Microsoft Word, so that there feels like there is more shortcuts and better ease of use. Icons for small caps, cut, and paste are incredibly helpful when you’re not sure what keyboard shortcuts are available. WordPerfect worked fine, but it just didn’t seem to have as many options that were as easy to use (and making tables was nearly impossible for me to understand). 
Other things on this Mac included MacDraw, Excel, PageMager, FileMaker, and Publishers. From the Excel files, I would say it’s past user worked for the University of Maryland and was helping to record statistics about the campus including student enrollment and class placement. The additions of PageMaker and FileMaker also make me think they were involved in campus publications of some sort. 
Other Notes: I love that we finally have the power button right on the keyboard again. I was missing the ease of this turning on the older computers. This computer is the first one to really remind me of my own computer, but of course like the Amiga it has drives whereas my Air really has no places to input drives but the USBs (so not so many videos for me). Also I loved the idea of MacDraw—I don’t think my Mac now has a space for that. 
